events.name: Dispatches from the Field: Kim Frank
events.description:
Dispatches from the Field, a new digital program designed to bring The Explorers Club community closer—wherever you are. 
Each session kicks off with a 10-minute talk from a Featured Speaker, streamed live to the public on explorers.org and our YouTube channel. 
This will be followed by Campfire sessions—intimate, Members-Only breakout groups where you can connect, share ideas, and build relationships. 
  
This edition features Kim Frank FN’18, to present Into the Unknown: The Art of Expedition Storytelling: 
Exploration is about venturing into unknown and sharing what you’ve learned. The most compelling stories from the field bring together diverse cultures, scientific discoveries, and and personal journeys, resonating with a broader audience. Drawing from my experiences documenting the human-elephant conflict in India, I’ll share how expedition storytelling can inspire action and deepen our connection with each other and the natural world. 
Members only – click here to register.

events.name: Eyewitness to War
events.description:
Eyewitness to War: A Reporter’s Quest for Truth Amid a Landscape of Death and Deception
  
Join Explorers Club fellow and award-winning journalist Scott Wallace for a startling look into the armed conflicts that rocked Central America in the 1980s. 
  
This richly illustrated multimedia lecture will take the audience on an unforgettable journey into the jungles and bullet-scarred villages of Central America during the upheaval of the 1980s. Danger lurks at every turn as Scott Wallace ventures up rebel-infested mountain roads, boards helicopters buzzing the treetops to dodge heat-seeking missiles, and travels by dugout canoe along hotly contested waterways in his quest to uncover the truth. Based on his new visual and written memoir, Central America in the Crosshairs of War, the lecture will also raise timely questions about U.S. foreign policy, the uses of American military power, and the origins of the current immigration crisis on the southern border. This lecture will especially appeal to those interested in the intersection of exploration and war reportage, human and Indigenous rights, war photography, and the business of reporting the news in a time of widespread deception and disinformation. 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. Scott will also have copies of his book available for signing.

events.name: Invisible Iceberg: When Climate and Weather Shaped History
events.description:
Join The Explorers Club on Monday, March 3rd to learn about the wild, unexpected, and fascinating ways that weather has influenced and altered the outcomes of momentous events throughout history. 
AccuWeather Founder and Executive Chairman Dr. Joel N. Myers takes readers on a journey from the beginning of time to modern days, exploring how weather and climate impacted historic events around the globe in his book Invisible Iceberg: When Climate and Weather Shaped History. 
From the comet that ended the age of the dinosaur 66 million years ago, to engrossing stories about how weather and climate led to the rise and fall of empires, caused plagues to spread, inspired works of art, and thoughts on whether the movements of a cold front and a nearby hurricane could have thwarted the 9/11 attacks, the book highlights dozens of fascinating events from history, along with thought-provoking insight about how weather and climate are stitched into the outcomes of these historic occurrences.

events.name: Anne Morrow Lindbergh: Visionary Aviator and Explorer
events.description:
Join the Explorers Club and the Breaking Barriers committee on March 10th to celebrate the life of pioneering author and explorer Anne Morrow Lindbergh. 
  
On May 27th, 1929, Anne Spencer Morrow, a quite shy, prize-winning English major and graduate of Smith College, married Charles A. Lindbergh, the most famous aviator of his time and the world’s first media star. Not surprisingly this changed her life radically. In five years, by 1934, she would be referred to in the media as the “First Lady of Aviation” on her own merits. This amazing transformation would not only include her learning to fly, getting her radio license, and becoming a fully licensed glider pilot, but also opened the door to many very real flying accomplishments and adventures as she accompanied her husband as navigator, radio operator, and co-pilot, exploring the uses of aviation, then a new technology, in exploration, science, communication, and relief work. 
Anne’s contributions to exploration include: 

Acting as co-pilot and navigator with her husband to set a transcontinental record.
Spotting from the air an important and previously undiscovered Mayan temple.
Photo-documenting areas of the Canyon de Chelly that are still extremely difficult to reach.
Identifying a previously unknown mountain range in Greenland.
Flying 40,000 miles with her husband acting as co-pilot, radio operator, and navigator, surveying national and international air routes, many still in use today.
Making a record breaking radio transmission of 3,000 miles, establishing a new long distance record.

Her two books on her flying experiences during the Golden Age of Flight were best sellers and won the National Bookseller Association National Book Awards for non-fiction. Her first book, NORTH TO THE ORIENT, marking it’s 90th year in print in 2025, won the first National Book Award for non-fiction in 1935.

events.name: Nanuk Narratives
events.description:
Nanuk Narratives: Voices of the People Living Alongside Polar Bears
  
“Nanuk Narratives” is an Inuit-led series of short documentary films about the deep and enduring relationship among Inuit and polar bears (nanuk). Hearing directly from Inuit across the Canadian Arctic and Greenland, these videos explore a diversity of topics, including Inuit observations of bear abundance and health, human-bear encounters and safety, tracking and hunting bears, cooking and eating bears, the cultural and emotional connections to bears, and Inuit recommendations for polar bear management. 
This event will be presented by David Borish, the director of this initiative, who is also an EC50 Class of 2023 member. David will screen a variety of short films that hear from community voices, and talk about the process of co-creating films in partnership with Inuit communities, wildlife co-management boards, local filmmakers, researchers, and others. David will also share his experience filming polar bears across the Arctic, including skidooing in temperatures below -40 fahrenheit, and the sailing through the Northwest Passage on Le Commandant Charcot icebreaker.

events.name: Blown Away - Searching for the Legendary Khamsin Winds
events.description:
Sometimes, one moment on an expedition can be so impactful it changes the way we think about the world around us, even for a veteran explorer familiar with the area. This is what happened to Tom Paradise and his team when the fierce Khamsin desert winds enveloped his expedition party in Wadi Rum last year. Join Tom and The Explorers Club for a personal account and investigation into this powerful phenomenon.  
Having worked in southern Jordan since 1990, Tom Paradise has slept in Bedouin tents, studied the desert, climbed Mount Nebo and Jebel Haroun – the legendary burial sites of Moses and his brother Aaron, and has documented hundreds of Nabatean tombs and monuments. However, the rare, and often ferocious Khamsin winds have constantly eluded Paradise and his teams. However, in May 2024, when on an Explorers Club Flag Expedition in Wadi Rum near the Saudi border, he and his group were fortuitously loaded with field equipment when the extraordinary winds hit. Lasting only 83 minutes, the southerly winds stirred up the desert floor creating a solid wall of dust and sand.  The gales gusted up to 100 kph (65mph) while the team recorded the dramatic event. Not only was it an outrageous experience, these ‘winds of legend‘ profoundly challenged our understanding about desert landforms and environmental dynamics. Was such a rare and savage episode able to change the desert cliffs and dune fields blowing only a few hours each year, or was it our current conventional theories of everyday processes (uniformitarianism) that truly change the landscape around us?  For a team of veteran field geoscientists and grad students, our way of looking at desert landforms was changed forever…

events.name: Navigating Drought: Predators, People, and Coexistence
events.description:
When faced with drought, how do Africa’s great predators adjust their behavior to survive? Join Leigh West, a wildlife researcher and Explorers Club grantee, as she shares how lions, leopards, cheetahs, and African wild dogs change their movements when water sources dwindle and prey becomes scarce. Discover how these predators interact with one another and share the landscape with people as they adapt to increasingly frequent and severe environmental challenges. 
Through captivating stories from her fieldwork in Botswana’s Okavango Delta, Leigh will reveal how understanding predator behavior during extreme climate events can help foster coexistence between people and wildlife. Using 13 years of GPS data from these carnivores encompassing several droughts, Leigh’s research highlights how drought can reshape carnivore behavior, from shifting movement patterns to changing exposure to humans, and has direct implications for conservation in a changing climate. 
Perfect for adventurers, conservationists, and anyone fascinated by the resilience of wildlife and the challenges of living alongside them!

events.name: Saving India's Wildlife
events.description:
Join the Explorers Club and Wildlife SOS for a look into past and ongoing efforts to preserve India’s threatened wildlife. 
Wildlife SOS is widely recognized for one of India’s most remarkable conservation successes—the eradication of the cruel practice of dancing bears. Building on this achievement, the organization is applying its expertise to tackle other pressing wildlife conservation challenges in India, including the protection of Asian elephants. 
Asian elephants are an endangered species, with fewer than 40,000 individuals remaining worldwide. Over 60% of this population is found in India, making the country critical to the species’ long-term survival. Indian elephant populations face significant threats, including habitat fragmentation, human-wildlife conflict, and the ongoing demand for elephants in captivity. Wildlife SOS is working to both improve the welfare of captive elephants as well as implementing creative strategies to protect them in the wild. 
Kartick Satyanarayan, Wildlife SOS co-founder, and one of the world’s most notable wildlife warriors, will be telling stories from his experiences in the field to conserve and protect India’s wildlife.

events.name: Summiting Everest Without Oxygen
events.description:
Join the Explorers Club and famed alpinist Melissa Arnot Reid for a first hand account of her journey to become the first American woman to summit Everest without supplemental oxygen. 
In May of 2016 Melissa Arnot Reid became the first American woman to summit Mount Everest without the use of supplemental oxygen. It was her sixth summit of the peak and the culmination of nine seasons of working as a mountain guide on Everest and around the world. The journey to arriving at the summit, and surviving the descent, was one filled with physical and emotional challenges that required her to dive deep into her own motivation for being there and face the truth of the life and death stakes of trying something nearly impossible. To celebrate the release of her memoir, ENOUGH: CLIMBING TOWARD A TRUE SELF ON MOUNT EVEREST, Melissa will share the story behind her motivation, the road to being ready, and the details of her historic climb–most of which have never been shared publicly. A story of personal reflection, growth, and healing on the highest peak on earth containing lessons learned in the mountains, but of use to everyone regardless of what your own mountain is in life. 
  
 
  
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A. Books will be available for purchase.

events.name: Further Explorations of the Titanic
events.description:
On the evening of April 14—113 years after the Titanic struck the iceberg that sealed its fate—this presentation explores three areas of study worth continuing on the legendary vessel.  
First, we’ll examine how the Titanic serves as a living laboratory for marine biologists and oceanographers. The wreck has become an unprecedented case study of deep-sea decomposition, offering insights into how metal structures deteriorate in extreme conditions and supporting unique ecosystems of “rusticles” and specialized microorganisms. 
The second segment addresses the ongoing ethical debate surrounding salvage operations. We’ll analyze the tension between preserving historical artifacts and maintaining the site’s integrity as a maritime grave, examining recent court decisions and competing claims from salvage companies and preservation groups. 
Finally, we’ll delve into the often-overlooked ethnic diversity among Titanic’s passengers. While popular media typically focuses on wealthy first-class travelers from the United States and United Kingdom, the ship carried a rich tapestry of immigrants from across Europe, the Middle East, and Asia. We’ll explore the stories of passengers from places like Lebanon, Croatia, and even China, examining their reasons for travel and how their experiences reflect broader patterns of early 20th-century migration. 
Together, these perspectives offer fresh insights into one of history’s most studied maritime disasters, demonstrating that science will carry Titanic’s legacy forward as much as legend. 
  
Schwankert’s new book The Six will be available for purchase and signing after the presentation. 
This in-person event at the Explorers Club Headquarters will include an audience Q&A.

events.name: Derek Parfit's Birthday!
events.description:
Derek Parfit was perhaps the greatest moral philosopher of the 20th century, in how he shaped the discipline and raised important new questions. 

He gave us the Repugnant Conclusion and the Hitchhiker's Dilemma, and put a plug for giving 10% into On What Matters, his masterpiece. Had he lived long enough to finish another volume, he had plans to discuss existential risk and dive deeper into questions of how we ought to act.

How to celebrate Parfit's life and work? You could discuss population ethics, philosophize about something else, or consider, as a group, ways to make your lives slightly more rational. (Or just eat cake and sing Happy Birthday and engage in idle, friendly conversation; Parfit surely wouldn't object.)

More info on the Empire TNS webpage.

events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Prospect Park loop organized by the Empire and Brooklyn Speed Teams.

Practices are held Sunday mornings from the start of April until the end of September, but may begin in March and end in October if weather and temperatures permit.

Meet-up is at the Bartel-Pritchard Circle entrance to Prospect Park, at the intersection of Prospect Park West and 15th St. Start time varies from 8:30 or 9 a.m. most of the summer but may be later in spring and autumn, depending on expected general use of the loop. So always check in with the Empire Speed FB page and/or with other skaters beforehand to find out exactly when it is.

The first loop is usually a warm up loop, and new-ish speedskaters should be able to hang on. After that the pace speeds up, and slower skaters may have to form a B group.

events.name: Empire-Brooklyn Speed Training
events.description:
Group inline speedskating practice on the Prospect Park loop organized by the Empire and Brooklyn Speed Teams.

Practices are held Sunday mornings from the start of April until the end of September, but may begin in March and end in October if weather and temperatures permit.

Meet-up is at the Bartel-Pritchard Circle entrance to Prospect Park, at the intersection of Prospect Park West and 15th St. Start time varies from 8:30 or 9 a.m. most of the summer but may be later in spring and autumn, depending on expected general use of the loop. So always check in with the Empire Speed FB page and/or with other skaters beforehand to find out exactly when it is.

The first loop is usually a warm up loop, and new-ish speedskaters should be able to hang on. After that the pace speeds up, and slower skaters may have to form a B group.

events.name: Pre-Marathon Speed Skate
events.description:
Informal (as in, not sponsored by any organization) group skate following the course of the NYC Marathon before the runners take over. This is a fast paced skate for advanced skaters. Group will start rolling ASAP and will endeavor to follow as much of the course as possible before the Queensboro Bridge is blocked off and before the streets are closed off by the police. If skaters make good time, they can roll over the QBB traffic lanes without (OMG, the embarrassment) taking the subway across the East River.

Safety/health notice: Helmet and other protective gear are strongly recommended.

Level: Advanced

events.name: Empire Sunday Marathon Watching Skate
events.description:
Group skate to watch runners in the NYC Marathon.

Group meets at Dante Park at Broadway and West 63rd St (across from Lincoln Center) at 9:30 a.m. and skates to East Harlem to see the lead runners heading up First Ave. and again as they head down Fifth Ave. Afterwards, the group will roll around upper Manhattan and the Bronx to watch and cheer on later runners. The group might also make a visit to the Bronx Brewery and/or Yankee Stadium and/or the High Bridge and/or a skate-friendly restaurant.

This group skate will include skating on city streets. Skaters must be accustomed to skating alongside city traffic.

Safety/health notice: Helmet and protection gear are strongly recommended.

Level: Intermediate
